ign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usiryakk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#ffffff>(8/22/02 10:41 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> The Damage Dealer Balance Problem</span><hr size=1> XP in this game comes down to killing creatures.<br>
<br>
In effect, your rate of XP in this game is how much DPH you can cause, divided by the number of players required to maintain this DPH.<br>
<br>
Keeping a heavy damage dealing class like a wizard balanced is hard.<br>
<br>
If they do significantly above average damage, why would they group?(1)  Every individual added who does less damage per hour than the wizard lowers the groups average DPH, plus adds coordination friction.(2)<br>
<br>
Verant solved the problem for Rogues by requiring the Rogue to be behind the target -- requiring a support infrastructure of some kind for the Rogue to keep up her DPH.  Either fear/hate kiting of some kind, or a tank+healer combo in order to soak up the damage.<br>
<br>
However, Wizards do not have the Rogue problem, at least on non-summoning creatures.  They can snare, root and jboot kite them -- even indoors some places.<br>
<br>
Similarly, the Monk is often seen soloing (traditionally) -- able to keep up their HPs using mend and bind wounds, their above average DPS translates into very good DPH.(3)<br>
<br>
Then, there are the column spells -- these spells are NOT easy to use in a group at all -- producing the inducement to quad kite rather than group.<br>
<br>
Wizards are hurt by this, because it means Verant has, at least in the past, kept their DPH down BELOW the average DPH in a group.  As their DD DPH passes the average, it becomes more and more tempting to use DDs to kill the creatures, solo, rather than bothering with the group baggage.(4)<br>
<br>
And if a damage dealing class, in a group, has a lower DPH than average -- well, their choice as a group member is not exactly optimal.  This sucks.<br>
<br>
There are other reasons to group other than DPH -- if tougher camps give more XP, with creatures/multiples that are harder than 1 person can deal with, grouping becomes useful.(5)<br>
<br>
Another reason to group is synergy -- haste, clarity, and other abilities your group members bring that make the group more powerful than the sum of its parts.  2.5+ hour buffs have reduced this synergy -- how many Wizards buy a KEI every 2.5 hours, or get one off a guildie?  How many melees bug friendly enchanters for a haste from their clicksticks while soloing?(6)<br>
<br>
I think this is a tricky problem.  And I don't know how to solve it.<br>
<br>
Maybe Verant's plan to make tougher creatures worth killing will help.  Or larger XP bonus' in new, tougher zones.<br>
<br>
Remember, wizards are not just being balanced against other damage dealers.  Tanks and Support must be factored in as well.<br>
<br>
Footnotes:<br>
(1) Other than socialization.  =)<br>
<br>
(2) coordination friction, or time lost.  People going AFK.  Gathering.  Random LD.  You know what I'm talking about.<br>
<br>
(3) Their ability to spell haste 40%, and FD in overpulls, also helps.<br>
<br>
(4) MB =)<br>
<br>
(5) Most dungeons used to be like this, and CT is mostly like this.  Now, Velks and Upper Seb is soloable by high level melees with ease.<br>
<br>
(6) I use Enchanters as an example, because traditionally they are the best at improving DPH with buffs.  Cheap &amp; Long lasting buffs make actually GROUPing with the buffer less likely.<br>
