 Dlaren <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugoladus.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goladus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<br>Err, Forum Arch Mage?</span><br>  Posts: 2411<br> <font color=#ffffff>(8/27/02 1:21 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Damage Dealer Balance Problem</span><hr size=1> I don't want to talk about mage versus wizard balance in this thread...  You're trying to hijack the thread by bringing up this topic.  It's about damage dealing in xp groups only.<br>
<br>
If the changes on test go live and are as significant as they seem, then this thread will be rather obselete anyway.<br>
<br>
It fixes the dichotomy of wizards in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> raids</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> versus xp groups by making <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> raids</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> reward appropriate xp.  And when I say raid I mean raids 1-60, ranging from a Pixie Trickster to An Ancient Guardian Wurm... Where <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> raid</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> means a single combat objective.<br>
<br>
Ideally, it will mean that a group that kills a mob 5 levels higher than them and rests after every pull will get the same xp as the group that kills 10 mobs 5 levels below with no downtime.  Furthermore, the group grinding the 10 mobs with no downtime should take longer to kill the stronger mob and still possibly suffer downtime, and might possible not be capable of killing it at all.  However,  the group that killed the red mob may not be capable of grinding low blues as quickly as the other group.<br>
<br>
When I was arguing against the pet xp penalty, I showed how a dichotomy formed between what the goal of the game <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> should</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be and what the goal of a magician actually was.<br>
<br>
A magician suffering from the 50% pet penalty was faced with a choice.  He could play his class to try to realize his full potential in killing mobs as quickly as possible, -OR- he could try to realize maximum xp gain by using strategies that didn't really make sense (overnuke the pet, reclaim at the end, memory blur.. etc).  For every non-pet class the goal of gaining xp and the goal of killing mobs quickly were one and the same.  A non-pet class doesn't change its strategy to be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> less</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> effective versus mobs in order to gain <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> greater</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> xp.  This was my problem with the pet xp penalty and why I argued so vehemently for it to be removed.  You were playing the game to get xp, not playing the game and being rewarded with xp.  And yes.. I admitted that one possible solution was to impose a constant penalty, which VI chose not to do.<br>
<br>
This situation is very similar.  Experience should be the reward for playing the game and accomplishing things.  It should reward better play.  The division of goals is not so clear cut here, but nonetheless the division is still there.  Groups choose to &quot;play&quot; the game in a boring fashion because it gains more xp.  In many cases, significantly more xp.  But that's not really playing, that's working.  The whole concept of &quot;grinding&quot; is a rather bad one.  <br>
<br>
Actually, the fact that the game is reduced to &quot;grinding xp&quot; actually lends a lot of weight to the &quot;We're fine at 60 argument.&quot;  Since, for so many, the game has been reduced to gaining pp and xp for 59 levels before starting to have fun, true game balance during that time doesn't matter.  It also lends weight to the soloing argument and the AE group argument.<br>
<br>
The problem is not the classes.  The problem is how those classes fit into the game as it is played, and, more specifically, the problem is the way people play the game.<br>
<br>
While making the pet argument I used two analogies to help illustrate the point, and both apply here.<br>
<br>
When a student takes a test, normally his goal is to demonstrate knowledge and ability by answering questions.  The student should be scored based on how well he performs.  For a multiple choice test, however, something changes.  If a student does not know the answer to a question, he can randomly guess the correct answer.  If an incorrect answer is scored the same as no answer, then certian scores may be inflated.  A student in this environment thus has an illogical (what I called &quot;external&quot;) goal-- that of getting a good grade on the test.  The goal of getting a good grade is separated from the goal of demonstrating knowledge because, through random guessing, a student can get a score that is not really a reflection on his knowledge, rather his ability to fill in bubbles on an answer sheet.<br>
<br>
This is why on tests like the Advanced Placement exams, tests are scored by giving points for a correct answer, zero points for no answer, and negative points for incorrect answers.  A student in this environment is encouraged to answer every question he can without resorting to random guessing.  Normally, a test is balanced such that educated guessing (when you can narrow it down to a small number of choices) will result in a better score.<br>
<br>
Another point:  If you were to totally remove the scoring system i.e. if you were taking the test for yourself alone, you would not guess.  You would probably take the test identically to the way you would take it if it was scored using the AP method.    <br>
<br>
I liken the ability to guess and earn points on a multiple choice test to flattening low blue mobs under the grind-machine of a sustained-dps oriented group.  If you were to totally remove the xp/loot system from everquest, no one would ever &quot;grind xp.&quot;  People would kill things for the challenge of it and to say they'd done it.  Of course not too many people would play eq if you took out character advancement..  But the point is that if you consider that orange bar to be a scoring system as I do, you'll find that you'll play the game differently if it's not there.  <br>
<br>
I think that is something that could/should be improved.  Getting xp should not require such a departure from the way you might ordinarily play the game.<br>
<br>
The second example I used was an america football game.  Football is a game that is played in backyards as well as professionally.  Often, when pickup games are played, score is not even kept... yet the game remains basically the same.  Your goal is to get the football to the other team's end zone, and you have 4 chances to do so, and a chance to earn 4 more chances(first down).<br>
<br>
Suppose they were to add a rule that doubled the amount of points given on 3rd down.  This would totally change Football as we know it.  This would change the basic goal from &quot;get the ball into the other team's end zone&quot; to &quot;get the ball into the other team's end zone on 3rd down.&quot;  The game would probably still be fun and interesting, but now we would have a rather illogical goal.  Furthermore, the game would be played much differently in the absence of these rule.<br>
<br>
If these new xp changes work like they are supposed to, players should be rewarded appropriately with xp for playing the game as it was meant to be.  I'm sure it will not be perfect, but it will be a step in the right direction.  That is, making the goals of having fun and earning xp be one and the same.<br>
<br>
That is my interest in this thread.  At this point I am not overly concerned with how any one class fits in to this.  I'm thinking about the health of the game as a whole.   <p><center>
