<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Condensed version:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Experience should be the rewarded for playing the game and accomplishing things. It should reward better play.  The problem is that groups choose to &quot;play&quot; the game in a boring fashion because it gains more xp. In many cases, significantly more xp. But that's not really playing, that's working. The whole concept of &quot;grinding&quot; is a rather bad one.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Ideally</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->, Everquest would be played the same way by any given character whether experience existed or not.  I do not believe this goal is actually attainable, rather it is approachable.  I believe that right now, EQ is a long way from this goal.  (You can tell how the original EQ game designers tried for this.. albiet not necessarily very well, in that they hid xp gained from the player and used the vague and slow-moving orange bar)<br>
<br>
It's like the difference between taking a test that penalizes for guessing and one that doesn't.  The test that penalizes you is much more natural..  you take the test to demonstrate knowledge, not fill in bubbles on an answer sheet.  Grinding xp as opposed to being rewarded xp as you play for fun is like filling in bubbles on the test to get a better chance at a high score as opposed to answering the questions as best you can.<br>
<br>
I believe the proposed changes on test are a step in the right direction as far as solving this problem.<br>
